M. Licinium Crassum: a nobleman of high rank and enormous wealth, which he had got by speculating in real estate at the time of the terrorism of Sulla's proscriptions. He was possessed by an uneasy military and political ambition, and had won some credit as commander against the revolted slaves under Spartacus, ΒΕ. 71. He managed to get into office by the influence of his money, and by allying himself with more competent men, as P01npey(ss.c. 71 δε 60) and Caesar (13.0. 60). His inordinate ambition carried him at last into an enterprise too large for his powers, against the Parthian Empire, in which he lost his life, B.C. 53. His connection, as well as Caesar’s, with the reckless schemes of Catiline (see ἐξ 48, 49) is very doubtful, though believed by many scholars. It is not unlikely in itself, as both were ambitious and unscrupulous men, and knew, as Sallust says (ἓ 39), that the ablest and boldest man would in the end reap the fruits of the conspiracy : and that was Caesar.
